2Coming among those who are friendly, but not of the same party, pl isoners of war do not change their condition, except by special com- pact. As m the second league made between the Romans and Car- thaginians, it was agreed that those of the peoples, friends of Rome, who were taken prisoners by the Carthaginians, if they came into ports subject to the Romans, might claim their liberty3 and that the friends of the Carthaginians should have a like right. Therefore those of the Romans in the second Punic war, who, being prisoners, came into Greece on commercia] designs, had not there the right of postliminium, because the Greeks, in that war, had taken part with neither side: and therefore it was necessary for them to be ransomed‚ in order to regain their liberty.
